{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S4 â€” RFC 7662 token-introspection verifier\n\n## Why\nIntrospection completes the \"validate against an external Authorization Server\" story for\nproviders that issue **opaque** access tokens (or when instant revocation matters) â€” Keycloak,\nOkta, Auth0, WorkOS all expose a standard `/introspect` endpoint. It is the pattern the SDK's own\n`simple-auth` example demonstrates.\n\n## What\nAdd an **`IntrospectionTokenVerifier`** to `src/rebar/_mcp_auth.py`, registered on the composite\nseam, selected via `mcp.auth.strategies` with params `introspection_endpoint`, `client_id`,\n`client_secret_env` (the NAME of an environment variable holding the client secret â€” no plaintext\nsecret in the config file), `audience`, and optional positive-cache `ttl`. It POSTs the token to the endpoint\n(RFC 7662) with client authentication, accepts only `active: true` with a matching audience, and\nmaps `scope`/`exp`/`sub`/`client_id` into an `AccessToken`.\n\n## Approach & rationale\nModel on the SDK's shipped `IntrospectionTokenVerifier` example (the blessed reference) but add\nthe production hardening its docstring says it lacks: client authentication on the introspection\ncall, a short positive-only cache, and strict audience checking. Reuse the already-present `httpx`.\n\n## Scope\nThe introspection verifier only, on the S2 seam. Subset of the epic. Depends on S2. Independent of\nS3/S5/S6.\n\n## Security\nBoundary-crossing. Requirements: the client secret is read from the configured `client_secret_env` env var (never stored plaintext\nin config); the introspection call uses authenticated TLS (`client_secret_basic`) to an HTTPS-only\nendpoint (SSRF guard), bounded timeout; accept only\n`active:true` with a matching `aud` (RFC 8707); **fail-closed** on non-200/timeout/malformed\n(never treat an unreachable AS as allow); cache **positives only** with a TTL bounded by the\ntoken `exp` (never cache failures); never log the token.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Unit test (tier: unit against the real verifier; irreducible boundary â€” the introspection\n      HTTP call â€” is a stateful fake fed production-shaped RFC 7662 responses) asserts an\n      `active:true` response with a matching audience â†’ an `AccessToken` with the expected scopes.\n- [ ] Unit tests assert rejection (None) for: `active:false`; a non-200 response; a timeout/HTTP\n      error (fail-closed); and a mismatched `aud` â€” each a distinct negative control.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts positive results are cached for at most the configured TTL and never\n      beyond `exp`, and that a failure is not cached (observable oracle: second call within TTL\n      makes no HTTP call; a prior failure does).\n- [ ] Unit test asserts the introspection request carries client authentication and targets only\n      an HTTPS endpoint (observable oracle: the fake receives Basic auth; an http:// endpoint is\n      rejected at construction).\n- [ ] Integration test (httpx `ASGITransport`) asserts an introspection-validated token is\n      accepted (200) end-to-end.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive verifier, opt-in via `mcp.auth.strategies`. No change to other verifiers or stdio."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784065947256819001,"uuid":"055c81bf-a187-4535-9f81-68321fa46464"}